lenders.occupational_info:
I am from a small town near the border of Virginia and Tennessee. Nestled in the mountains, there isn't much of anything here- but that's alright with us. We are fiercely proud of local businesses, artisans and our southern heritage. 

I've been blessed to learn the ropes of the business world from my father and grandfather. My great-grandfather started our family furniture business in 1943. World War II was still raging and with most industrial efforts going toward the war effort, newly manufactured furniture was only available to dealers who could supply lumber to replenish the factory's needs. My great-grandfather, Oscar, would haul a load of Smyth County, Virginia lumber to North Carolina and bring back new furniture to sell. Most merchandise available for purchase in the store was items that had been used and were purchased in large cities such as Baltimore, Philadelphia, New York and Cincinnati. The business moved to Main Street in Marion in 1970 when the hotel was demolished. 

His spirit and determination remind me that success is in my blood. Besides a strong work ethic, my family has instilled in me a great sense of empathy. Being from an economically depressed area, a majority of our clients live below the poverty line. By extending credit when traditional methods fail them, we get to help someone every single day. Being invited into people's homes is one of the most rewarding things, and that is why we treat everyone like part of the family.
